"Rykaczewski R.R., Dunne J.P.","Enhanced nutrient supply to the California Current Ecosystem with global warming and increased stratification in an earth system model",2010,"Geophysical Research Letters","37","21", L21606,"","",,,10.1029/2010GL045019,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-78649287502&partnerID=40&md5=7bd615a69b46afdd70731ac6a3cf422b","Visiting Scientist Programs, University Corporation for Atmospheric Research, 201 Forrestal Rd., Princeton, NJ 08540-6649, United States; Geophysical Fluid Dynamics Laboratory, NOAA, 201 Forrestal Rd., Princeton, NJ 08540-6649, United States","Rykaczewski, R.R., Visiting Scientist Programs, University Corporation for Atmospheric Research, 201 Forrestal Rd., Princeton, NJ 08540-6649, United States; Dunne, J.P., Geophysical Fluid Dynamics Laboratory, NOAA, 201 Forrestal Rd., Princeton, NJ 08540-6649, United States","A leading hypothesis relating productivity with climate variability in the California Current Ecosystem (CCE) describes an alternation between warmer, well-stratified periods of low productivity and cooler periods of high productivity. This empirical relationship suggests that productivity will decline with global warming. Here, we explore the response of productivity to future climate change in the CCE using an earth system model. This model projects increases in nitrate supply and productivity in the CCE during the 21st century despite increases in stratification and limited change in wind-driven upwelling. We attribute the increased nitrate supply to enrichment of deep source waters entering the CCE resulting from decreased ventilation of the North Pacific. Decreases in dissolved-oxygen concentration and increasing acidification accompany projected increases in nitrate. This analysis illustrates that anthropogenic climate change may be unlike past variability; empirical relationships based on historical observations may be inappropriate for projecting ecosystem responses to future climate change. © 2010 by the American Geophysical Union.",,"Climatology; Dissolved oxygen; Earth (planet); Ecosystems; Global warming; Productivity; Anthropogenic climate change]; California Current; Climate variability; Deep source waters; Earth system model; Ecosystem response; Future climate; High productivity; Historical observation; North Pacific; Nutrient supply; Oxygen concentrations; Wind driven upwelling; Climate models; acidification; anthropogenic source; climate variation; concentration (composition); dissolved oxygen; ecosystem response; empirical analysis; global warming; nitrate; numerical model; nutrient availability; nutrient cycling; primary production; stratification; twenty first century; upwelling; ventilation; wind velocity; California Current; Pacific Ocean",,,,,,"Aksnes, D.L., Ohman, M.D., Multi-decadal shoaling of the euphotic zone in the southern sector of the California Current System (2009) Limnol. Oceanogr., 54, pp. 1272-1281; Bakun, A., Global climate change and intensification of coastal ocean upwelling (1990) Science, 247, pp. 198-201. , doi:10.1126/science. 247.4939.198; Bakun, A., Field, D.B., Redondo-Rodriguez, A., Weeks, S.J., Greenhouse gas, upwelling-favorable winds, and the future of coastal ocean upwelling ecosystems (2010) Global Change Biol., 16, pp. 1213-1228. , doi:10.1111/j.1365-2486.2009.02094.x; Behrenfeld, M.J., O'Malley, R.T., Siegel, D.A., McClain, C.R., Sarmiento, J.L., Feldman, G.C., Milligan, A.J., Boss, E.S., Climate-driven trends in contemporary ocean productivity (2006) Nature, 444 (7120), pp. 752-755. , DOI 10.1038/nature05317, PII NATURE05317; Bograd, S.J., Castro, C.G., Di Lorenzo, E., Palacios, D.M., Bailey, H., Gilly, W., Chavez, F.P., Oxygen declines and the shoaling of the hypoxic boundary in the California Current (2008) Geophys. Res. Lett., 35, pp. L12607. , doi:10.1029/2008GL034185; Capet, X.J., Marchesiello, P., McWilliams, J.C., Upwelling response to coastal wind profiles (2004) Geophysical Research Letters, 3